Deloitte internship: Represent the EBA DPM model from European banking authority as an ontology.
The data point model (DPM) dictionary implements the uniform and consistent definitions included in the implementing technical standards (ITS) and guidelines on reporting and disclosure. The data requirements of any regulatory amendments are translated and stored in the DPM repository containing the formal and structured representation of all data concepts, relations and quality rules shared by regulators, supervisors and institutions. The goal of this project is to represent the DPM model as an ontology and visualize the evolution of that over time.

"Write your own compiler" In this project, you will write a compiler for a programming language of your choosing in a language of your chosing. This is a project in a group in the following way: each student has his own project, his/her own compiler, and his/her own thesis, but the meetings with supervisor are group meetings. The group will be small 3-5 students. The idea of the group meetings is that you also see how the other students are progressing and that you can discuss approaches with each other. To participate you must be comfortable to share your project progress, as well as draft versions of your thesis with the group. You thesis will be about some research question you will answer using your own compiler, such as "how can a compiler optimize X for language Y" or how "how to design and implement a type system that does X". Up to 5 students can choose this project.

From probabilistic to complexity-based logic programming

Complexity measures from Algorithmic Information Theory generalize probabilistic measures, and in principle offer a non-extensional (including non-statistical) basis to perform inferences. In this project the student will explore the possibility to redefine a (simplified) probabilistic logic programming framework via complexity, in particular by exploiting the recent conjecture generalizing Bayes' rule in terms of complexity (https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-031-12429-7_8).

Data-flow language for Responsible AI

Most approaches emerging in the "responsible AI" field focus primarily on the problems relative to selecting and producing adequate data. One can for instance purge the input from sensitive elements, can for instance unbias the data used in the training, correct the parameters in the inference model, or add an external module to produce unbiased output at aggregate level. Alternatively, one can see the problem as a problem of data-flow: i.e. of adequately intervening or constraining the connections existing between the data processing components. This transforms the initial problem into one of "responsible" processing of data streams. The resulting distributed view allows to easy enrich the system with further layers eg. to compute distribution effects of data-use (to consider various types of distributive strategies) or other contextual dependency mechanisms. 

The project aims to explore the design and development of a computational framework for controlling ML modules, centred around a data-flow language for the coordination between processing component. Because relationships between input and output variables may be not deterministic, the language should consider an attribute to add uncertainty, similarly to what done in probabilistic logic programming (ProbLog, https://dtai.cs.kuleuven.be/problog/).

Note that the project is not about building new ML methods, but using them off-the-shelf. The desired framework, following a specification encoded in the target data-flow language,
- interacts with given modules (eg. to execute them for inference or for training)
- controls the communication channels between those modules (eg. to set up the data-flow topology)
- sets up investigations of existing modules (eg. to extract simplified decision-trees) 
- analyze the network for conflicts (eg. whether protected attributes or proxy variables have been used)

column5: Preference-based reward learning for robot social greeting behaviors. Preference-based learning is one of typical methods that utilize human feedback to solve robot learning problems. Previous work has attempted to combine this reward learning technique with Reinforcement Learning (RL) and apply it in structured simulation environments (e.g., OpenAI Gym). However, few work investigates its potential in solving social learning problems where real humans play the role as part of the environment. In this project, we propose to transfer social skills from human teachers to embodied robots via preference-based learning. Specifically, we will use human-robot social greeting as the benchmark task to test and demonstrate the resultant learning performance. As prerequisites, interested applicants are expected to be familiar with Reinforcement Learning. Coding experience with Pepper or Nao robots will be preferable, but is not necessary.
Programming robot motion through speech and gestures. This thesis project will be using ROS (https://www.ros.org/), which you will be expected to learn during the thesis.
Robot motion programming using a motion tracking suit
Puppeteering system for full body robot control

Hierarchical teaching system for a mobile social robot using speech - Speech is a powerful way to represent robot behaviors with hierarchical levels of complexity. For example, the behavior "greet" is composed of lower level behaviors "gaze", "approach", and "wave", each of which can be broken down further. In this project, you will be developing a speech-based system to teach robots complex behaviors from simple behavior primitives (or "building blocks"). You will also design an interaction flow where users can correct previously taught concepts, resulting in a fluid and intuitive way for people to teach robots new skills.
Learning from kinesthetic demonstrations on a robot arm.
Internship project in a robotics-related company (please contact me if you have an offer already)

Puppeteer me: kinesthetic corrections of robot motion - Kinesthetic demonstrations (i.e., puppeteering a robot through direct contact) is the most popular way of teaching robots how to perform physical tasks. In this project, you will be looking at how kinesthetic interactions can be used not as a demonstration but as a *correction*, meaning that the human can intervene while the robot is moving. In a first stage, you will develop a reactive module that allows the robot to detect when a human is intervening and allow the correction to happen. In a second stage, you will develop an algorithm for the robot to integrate the corrections into its initial behavior.
Robot improvisation by imitating expert policies

Reinforcement learning from audio feedback. In this project you will be developing a novel algorithm for agent learning from human audio feedback, such as "yes" and "no", in which prosody (e.g., tone of voice) will play a role

Robot learning from rich feedback. In this project, you will be implementing an interactive learning algorithm that allows the robot to learn from human input, including demonstrations and evaluative feedback. The algorithm will be tested on simple tasks involving robot body motion and potentially social behavior (speech, gazing behavior, etc.).

HAPSAH no-code natural language programming (multiple possible assignments)
Hapsah (https://www.hapsah.org/) is a no-code web application development platform that uses a controlled natural language programming model. It combines a Knowledge graph database and a Business rules engine into a an integrated model driven development platform. Based on the defined Knowledge / fact structure and business logic, it dynamically generates data entry screens, APIs into a live application without an explicit compiler or deployment phase. This makes Hapsah a truly agile development platform where the user is never required to possess any technical skills. For more information, check out our website: www.hapsah.org.

Project 1: Symbiosis between static knowledge graphs and dynamic business rules. How to combine fact-driven and action-driven approaches into one controlled natural language structure? Ik heb onlangs een boek mogen reviewen van Ronald Ross, een bekende naam in de wereld van natuurlijke taal business rules. Daarin staan zeer interessante dingen, maar hij hanteert een andere definitie van business rule dan ik. Hij zegt, business rules bevatten nooit concrete acties, terwijl ik dat juist wel zo zie. Ik zou hier graag meer onderzoek naar willen laten doen door een Master student. Dat is dus echt theoretisch onderzoek met mogelijk wat case studies om tot goede definities te komen. Eventueel zelfs onderbouwt door formele logica, maar dat is misschien een brug te ver ;-) Skills: Wetenschappelijk onderzoek (must)

Project 2: Make controlled natural language more natural. How to find the right balance in a controlled natural language between machine executability and human readability? Ook weer uit het nieuwe boek van Ronald Ross heb ik ideeen opgedaan hoe de controlled natural language bijvoorbeeld nog korter en bondiger kan (minder herhaling) of dynamischer (regels kunnen als statements maar ook als vragen worden geformuleerd als de gebruiker dat prettiger vindt). Ook dit is meer theoretisch onderzoek, mogelijk met een student die ook een minor in taalkunde heeft gedaan / aan het doen is. Skills: Wetenschappelijk onderzoek (must), Taalkunde (pre)

Project 3:How to generate knowledge graphs from a controlled natural language. Can the controlled natural language represent a unified knowledge structure that can be translated to any knowledge graph structure or ontology? Dit is een wat meer praktische opdracht waarbij vanuit de taalstructuur van Hapsah gekeken gaat worden hoe deze mapt op verschillende knowledge graph omgevingen / tools en of deze vanuit die mapping automatisch gegenereert kunnen worden. Deloitte internship: Data lineage insights on regulatory reporting and risk modeling based on Knowledge Graphs. Within Risk Advisory team at Deloitte, we help clients (large financial institutions) to build their end-to-end data-driven regulatory risk reporting and modelling pipelines. This starts from modelling regulatory requirements, towards sourcing those requirements and realization of them in a data warehouse or data lake. A common issue our clients face is tracking data throughout their lifecycle which is required by EU regulations such as BCBS239. Whether acquired externally or generated from internal services, data needs to be tracked as it is utilized, manipulated, and transformed throughout the reporting process. Knowledge Graphs allow companies to trace their data journey in the right context, to identify and fix gaps and broken links and to improve the quality of their data flows. In this project we focus on summarizing and visualizing the insights from our data lineage Knowledge Graph in a user-friendly way
- Create a 3D (metaverse) representation of data lineage, user study (HCI background)
- Create a 2D ERD visualization of data lineage, user study (React)

AI/IS for Colonial history. In the Pressing Matter (pressingmatter.nl) project, we are investigating in what ways digital methods can be used to look at Ownership, Value and the Question of Colonial Heritage in Museums. Potential projects within this framework are: 
1. Crowd-sourcing to formalise historical events while preserving many voices or different perspectives.
2. Sentiment analysis around these events. It could be interesting to analyse people’s perception of this event based on their background (museum expert vs commoner, east vs west...)
3. Drifting concept around a colonial object. The heritage objects connected to the “puputan” event have different narration (aggressive to more passive) in newspaper articles in different time-period, and also, there is a difference in museum narration on a similar object in museums in the Netherlands vs Museums in Indonesia.

"At the right place". In this Digital Humanities data project, you will collaborate with the Amsterdam city archive on enriching their data with geo-linked data. The aim is to provide existing metadata (e.g. indexes) with Adamlink uris after which the sources can be searched via a map viewer.
A brief explanation of the project is available online here (Some is in Dutch only, but the project does not require a native Dutch speaker):
https://www.amsterdam.nl/stadsarchief/organisatie/projecten/juiste-adres/
The newly added address data (previously we only had uris for streets) is here:
https://adamlink.nl/geo/addresses/start/
We also publish an occasional blog:
https://www.amsterdam.nl/stadsarchief/organisation/blog-brons-bytes/juiste-adres-(1)-marktkaarten/
https://www.amsterdam.nl/stadsarchief/organisation/blog-brons-bytes/juiste-adres-(2)-nooddorp-obelt-beeld/
https://www.amsterdam.nl/stadsarchief/organisation/blog-brons-bytes/juiste-adres-(3)-nieuwe-bedrijven/
Within the project I have room for an internship or a study assignment. I think it would be nice if a student could enrich a source with Adamlink uris. This requires (technical) knowledge to be able to make those new connections.

Confidential computing environment for multiparty computation
column8:
Extended description: Confidential Computing paradigm is primarily a response to create a secure trusted environment for data processing in clouds involving multiple parties while protecting data and algorithms. The concept and model have been actively developed in the recent two years involving key cloud providers and trusted computing companies that founded the Confidential Computing Consortium (CCC) that developed the Confidential Computing Framework (CCF). CCF combines hardware based Trusted Execution Environments (TEEs), decentralised systems concepts, and cryptography.
Implementations and cloud based services are available from Azure, AWS, IBM, Google. There is also an Open Source code.

column5: Policy continuum in multi-layer access and usage control for data processing in cloud
column8: Extended description: This project investigate challenges and will propose solutions to ensure multi-layer policy enforcement and usage control for data centric applications such as data exchange and sharing, multi-site long-running data processing workflow. Policy continuum should include system and application level access control as well as higher level compliance and (legal or governance) norms enforcement. In fact the project will bridge multiple existing solutions into consistent and secure policy controlled environment using such policy and assertion languages as XACML, SAML, interfacing with eFlint normative reasoning framework as well as integrating with the cloud based Federated AAI services. Such security mechanisms as session context, policy obligations, security tokens will be used.
